<FONT CLASS="title16">Arranging a Board</FONT><BR> 

<font class="bodyCopySmall">
A great cheese board is a rustic still life of wedges of Cheddar, ch&egrave;vres of 
various shapes and sizes, a perfect disk of Camembert swelling from its velvety white 
rind, and an emerald-and-sapphire Roquefort, on a board with a crusty baguette and 
a bowl of the fruits of the season. It's a simple work of art.
<P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" BORDER="0" WIDTH="379">
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Choose cheeses not only for their contrasting flavors and textures, but also for their different sizes and shapes and colors. Create a skyline of cheese.<BR><BR></TD> 
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Array your cheeses on a slab of marble, an old wooden cutting board, a wicker tray, or a shallow basket. Arrange them simply and leave space between them, so they are easy to cut.<BR><BR></TD> 
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Great cheese, like great wine, is best served at a cool room temperature. Cold cheese loses its flavor complexity and its texture.<BR><BR></TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Fresh seasonal fruit is a cheese's fondest companion, but don't muddle the board by sticking fruit in every available nook. Serve it on the side, in a simple bowl.<BR><BR></TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Crackers are fine, but they interfere with the texture of the cheese and break under the weight of all but the softest. Bread is better.<BR><BR></TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Little cubes of cheese are convenient for the mingling cocktailer, but they rob the cheese of its shape and identity (plus they dry out quickly and are tough to wrap and store). Keep the cheeses whole and let your guests cut what they need.<BR><BR></TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Use little cheese or butter knives for soft cheeses, a sturdy steak knife for harder ones.<BR><BR></TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN="top">
		<TD WIDTH="15"><img src="/media_stat/images/template/cheese/green_bullett.gif" width="6" height="6" border="0" HSPACE="4" VSPACE="3" ALIGN="RIGHT"></TD>
		<TD WIDTH="364" class="bodyCopySmall">Be creative with the accompaniments and garnish. Try walnut or raisin bread and a bowl of sweet pickles with a sharp Cheddar; a sprinkle of toasted walnuts with Roquefort; dried fruits, chutneys, and preserves with Etorki; or a drizzle of honey on mountain Gorgonzola.<BR></TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>
</font>
